                    <tr>
                      <td valign="top" height="100%"><font face="verdana" size="2" color="white"><span class="spnMessageText" id="msg"> In the wake of GoD, many talks about class balance and the resurgence of the Holy Trinity in high-difficulty grouping has resurfaced.  It's becoming increasingly obvious that some classes just aren't cut out for GoD trials and are mostly baggage that other, more important classes have to carry through.  Obviously, this is a failure, but in what way is it a failure? Is it a failure fundamental to EQ - ie something that will persist forever and always - or is it a failure of SoE's mentality in designing zones? <br /><br />Basically, my question is:<br /><br />Which one do you subscribe to?<br /><br />1. Class imbalance is fundamental to EQ and is a sign of poor design and lack of foresight by the original developers in introducing such mistakes as CH, Slow, Defensive, etc.  Solutions to this imbalance would involve a revamp of the EQ classes.<br /><br />2. Class imbalance rises from poorly balanced content and is not fundamental to EQ.  Namely, the equivalence of hard-hitting mobs with lots of hps with difficulty is the mentality that creates class imbalance.  Solutions to this imbalance would involve a rethinking of the way content is designed.<br /><br />3. Both.<br /><br />4. Neither.  <br /><br />5. Classes are balanced.<br /></span id="msg"></font></td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                      <td valign="bottom"><hr noshade size="1"><font color="white" face="verdana" size="2"><span class="spnMessageText"> Etadanik the Redeemed</span></font></td>
