                    <tr>
                      <td valign="top" height="100%"><font face="verdana" size="2" color="white"><span class="spnMessageText" id="msg"> <br />Both, with some reservations.<br /><br />The class imbalance is a fundamental problem caused by the fact that there are more classes than their are class roles. When the situation is severe enough to demand the "best", such as healing in GoD, then a class with diversity will lose out. When the situation is easy, such as XP grinding, the "best" class will lose out because they lack diversity. Mind you calling this an error on the part of the original designers is not really fair, it is unreasonable to expect them to have been able to completely foresee the path that EQ would develop along.<br /><br />Likewise encounters cannot be balanced because of the way in which class roles are apportioned. If they are hard for the generalists then they are easy for the specialists. If they are hard for the specialists they may well be impossible for the generalists. For example a druid attempting to heal in GoD or us attempting to match wizards for fast damage. Slow is the most famous example of massive differentiation, Defensive is another.<br /><br />The answer, I think, would have been to make multiple classes share a core ability. For example all offensive casters can do the same burst damage, all plate classes can tank the same and all priest classes can heal the same. You then only have classes if they can acceptably fill a core role (one can still be slightly better than another) and also have sufficient differentiation from one another.<br /><br />The more complex way is to have classes be equivalent in their ability even though their methods are different. I've heard it said that the priest classes where meant to be equivalent in this way. A shaman's slow and a druids damage shields (and regen for both) were meant to equal the slight superiority of cleric healing. But these systems tend to be fragile, as can be seen in EQ.<br /><br />All in all PoP was pretty silly and GoD just sounds surreal. The concept of them doing another expansion after GoD just blows my mind. Surely they've pushed the combat engine almost as far as it will go?<br /><br />Fun question though :)<br /><br /></span id="msg"></font></td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                      <td valign="bottom"><hr noshade size="1"><font color="white" face="verdana" size="2"><span class="spnMessageText"> Shinime Kanshi,<br />Arch-lich of Southern Armada.<br /></span></font></td>
