                    <tr>
                      <td valign="top" height="100%"><font face="verdana" size="2" color="white"><span class="spnMessageText" id="msg"> I agree with you Shinin in that it's a bit of both, but I tend to place more importance on the second view mostly because it's the view that, as far as I can tell, that can still be changed.<br /><br />It's unrealistic to think that SoE has any plans to revamp the classes & add major abilities to anyone of them.  The massive backlash that would create in the player base would simply devastate such an attempt and probably, as it did in most other cases of SoE trying to change the game, force a half-assed compromise.<br /><br />It is not as unrealistic to think that SoE can still improve on class balance by presenting better, more well thought of content.  Well, I should rephrase that: players would be more prone to accept new content than they would be to accept changes to existing content (ie classes).  This would probably be harder for SoE, however, so on a practical level I don't think it's likely we'll see anything from SoE.  Still, it's fun to theorize on what kind of content *would* alter class balance and how that could be used to equalize the sense of "self-importance" so vital to most people's enjoyment of the game.<br /><br />It's really a fun and interesting issue to debate, and I hope more people would join in :)<br /></span id="msg"></font></td>
                    </tr>
