                    <tr>
                      <td valign="top" height="100%"><font face="verdana" size="2" color="white"><span class="spnMessageText" id="msg"> <br />For sure. Everyone knows that slow, defensive and complete heal are wildly imbalanced. But if you downgrade the importance of any of them the respective classes will explode. Really that's part of the problem, expecting to be able to grow the game while keeping the classes largely static is simply not going to work. They could solve it by having "prestige" or "hero" classes come out that actually re-jig the class balance. For example a L65 necromancer can convert into some other "class" which will in time progress to being better adapted to the environment than someone who remains as a pure necromancer. But this is a whole heap of work and I suspect SOE figure they can't sell it. And if they can't sell it they won't do it.<br /><br />In fact that's the real problem I guess. They don't feel they can sell an expansion on the basis of "new worlds to explore!" but know they can sell it on the basis of power progression. Thus each expansion must invalidate the previous which leads to exponential growth in power.<br /><br />And there are limits to what can be acheived in the encounter design. Take slow. Either you marginalize the ability by making everything resistant, which means shaman are screwed without substantial re-design, or you have to balance on the basis of it being present. If you balanced the encounter to be challenging with slow then it's probably downright impossible without.<br /><br />Rogues work the other way around. The design calls for them to be picking locks, sensing and disarming traps. But you can't make this class role that important because doing so would screw over all groups without a rogue. Which is why the LDoN chests are such an abortion (well, apart from them having a warped view of risk vs. reward), they can't afford to make them worthwhile because groups without rogues will whine.<br /><br />Horizon's and SWG solve this problem by their being effectively no classes. Of course this means that group inter-dependancy is lost and tactics tend to be dull. It's hard to tell much about WoW balance, because the information is incomplete, but certainly the fact that the game realises that fewer classes = better class balance is heartening.<br /></span id="msg"></font></td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                      <td valign="bottom"><hr noshade size="1"><font color="white" face="verdana" size="2"><span class="spnMessageText"> Shinime Kanshi,<br />Arch-lich of Southern Armada.<br /></span></font></td>
