                      <td valign="top" height="100%"><font face="verdana" size="2" color="white"><span class="spnMessageText" id="msg"> I have to agree with whoever mentioned classes should be proportionally balanced (ie Clerics healing to druids dmg shield to shaman's slow).  That way there would be some clear defining role for everyone and you could set up your groups according to their key component.<br /><br />However I do lay the blame at the "same ole same ole" concepts straight on the developers feet.  BECAUSE of mudflation, because of uber gear, they REQUIRE insane DPS mobs, but beyond the Tank/Clr/slower (which half the time is pointless because it seems in GoD you get the cannot be slowed message more times than most slowers would like) people can't see out of the box.  Or don't want to waste time trying new things or new combinations.<br /><br />The ingrained ideas are also what contributes to these cycles in EQ.  Because the players continue to always use the tank/cleric/slower combo the devs will still build content around it.<br /><br />At this point in EQ I find that classes are not balanced.  And if you're trying the higher end god things (Temple trials and whatnot) you're going to find specific classes being passed over 90% of the time.  They are simply baggage.<br /><br />Yes, they may bring DPS, but when you could have XXX DPS instead and have XXX's ability to do Y, why would you want DPS_Class_07?<br /><br />If you're lucky you can overcome this "class imbalance" by finding friends or setting up your own groups.  But that is not the point.  The content isn't designed for EVERYONE to play.  It simply isn't anymore.  It's designed for very specific groups to do things in very specific ways.<br /><br />Unfortunately I'm super tired and cannot fathom a way to bring about class balance in EQ without rehauling the enitre game... but isn't that EQ2?</span id="msg"></font></td>
                    </tr>
